//! RAII-2 (#1295): a `#[resource]` passed as a NON-RECEIVER argument to an
//! `impl` method drops exactly once.
//!
//! `combine` borrows its receiver (it only reads `self.id`) and takes a second
//! `#[resource]` value `other`. Per the ratified borrow-default surface the
//! borrow-site collector never downgrades a method-call argument — a receiver
//! carries authoritative move intent that must not be relaxed, so the whole
//! arg list is skipped — and `other` reaches the call site with its
//! HIR-over-stamped `Consume` intent. The caller therefore MOVES `other` in and
//! does not auto-drop it. The callee must own it: `compute_param_ownership`
//! force-classifies a method's non-receiver resource parameter CONSUME, adding
//! it to the callee's `owned_locals` so `combine` drops it at its own scope
//! exit.
//!
//! Without that classification neither side dropped `other`: the caller moved
//! it in (so it did not auto-drop) and the callee left it BORROW (so
//! `lower_params` did not drop it) — a leak / split ownership.
//!
//! Observable contract: `combine` consumes `other` and drops it at its scope
//! exit (prints `7`); `main` keeps `a` (the borrowed receiver) and auto-drops
//! it at its scope exit (prints `3`). Each id prints exactly once. A regression
//! that re-introduced the leak would print only `3`; a double-free would print
//! `7` twice and abort at the resource sentinel.

#[resource]
type R {
    id: i64;
}

impl R {
    fn close(self) {
        println(self.id);
    }

    fn combine(self, other: R) -> i64 {
        self.id + other.id
    }
}

fn main() -> i64 {
    let a = R { id: 3 };
    let b = R { id: 7 };
    let _total = a.combine(b);
    0
}
